=== Box-office and ratings ===
Released with a "U" (Universal: Suitable for all ages) certification by the [[Central Board of Film Certification]] of India,, ''Parineeta'' notched up [[Indian rupee|Rs.]] 206 million in India at the end of 2005.<ref name="boxoffice">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://www.ibosnetwork.com/asp/filmbodetails.asp?id=Parineeta+(2005)
|title=International Business Overview Standard}}</ref> Its overseas success was notable as well with gross collections of Rs. 36 million in the United Kingdom, Rs. 35 million in North America, and Rs 15 million in the rest of the overseas.<ref name="boxoffice1">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/overseas.htm
|title=BoxOfficeIndia.com - Overseas}}</ref>

=== Reviews, critiques and controversies ===
Prior to the film's release on [[June 10]], [[2005]], one preview wondered how the film would fare at the box office. Citing comparisons with the [[Parineeta (1953 film)|1953 version]], the preview suggested that debutant director, Sarkar's inexperience in film making, the probable inability of debutant actress, Balan to portray ''Lolita's'' character appropriately, suitable 1960s depiction by contemporaries, Sanjay Dutt and Saif Ali Khan, and musician, Shantanu Moitra's until then unimpressive soundtracks, could be impediments for the film to be a successful adaptation.<ref name="bollywoodcritics">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://www.bollywood.com/archives/2005/06/parineeta_could.html
|title='Parineeta could rekindle soft, nostalgic feelings...'|first=Subhash K.|last=Jha}}</ref>

Post-release, the same critic said "Vidhu Vinod Chopra's "Parineeta" - a remake of an old classic of the same name...(had) the love story (which) was received well by the younger generation and it went on to become the biggest hit of the year."<ref name="bollywoodcritics1">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://www.bollywood.com/archives/2006/10/why_is_bollywoo.html
|title=Why is Bollywood obsessed with remakes|first=Arpana|last=Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> The film was generally well-received by the critics<ref name="pbollywoodcritics">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://planetbollywood.com/Film/Parineeta/
|title=Film Review - Parineeta|first=Alok|last=Kumar}}</ref>, with one of them terming the movie as "...a beautiful story, beautifully told. It approximates what most of us expect, and increasingly yearn for, in vain, our cinematic experience."<ref name="rediffcritics">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2005/jun/10pari.htm
|title=Parineeta is a must watch|first=Dinesh|last=Raheja}}</ref> A reviewer from About.com said that it is "contemporary retelling of...(an) engaging and timeless tale rich with human emotion and universal drama". The reviewer appreciates the film in most of the nuances of film making saying that this is "enhanced by a brilliant musical score, and accentuated by superb performances by Sanjay Dutt, Saif Ali Khan, Raima Sen, Diya Mirza and debutante Vidya Balan in the lead role of Lolita".<ref name="aboutcritics">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://hinduism.about.com/od/moviestillsreviews/a/parineeta.htm
|title=Parineeta, The Married Woman|first=Subhamoy|last=Das}}</ref> A news report from ''[[The Times of India]]'' states that 3000 copies of the novella were sold within weeks of the films release, owing to the film's good reception.<ref name="novellasales">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1156282.cms
|title='Parineeta': the hot new bestseller|first=Avijit|last=Ghosh}}</ref> 

About the movie, Derek Elley from [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] said "A character-driven meller that's a treat for the eyes, with performances to match, "Parineeta" is high-end Bollywood near its best". He also says that, "... though the climax is still emotionally powerful, it comes over as overcooked."<ref name="varietycritics">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117929519.html?categoryId=31&cs=1
|title=Parineeta: Film Review|first=Derek|last=Elley}}</ref> A mixed review from ''[[Mid-Day]]'' that says "Pradeep Sarkar weaves the story like magic, especially in the first half ... excelling in the detailing ... the vintage look of the film (that stood out) with authentic costumes, props and the roads of Kolkata". However, the review criticised the film's climax terming it as amateur, thereby diluting the whole film's impact.<ref name="middaycritics">{{cite news|first=Sarita|last=Tanvar|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://www.mid-day.com/hitlist/2005/june/111357.htm
|title=Film Review: Parineeta}}</ref> Another such review came from ''[[The Hindu]]'' which begins by saying "A simple enough story, but Sarkar tells it well, with some great shots of Shekhar and Lolita together. The review eventually says "Except for the end ... where it is too much to bear."<ref name="hinducritics">{{cite news|first=Susan|last=Muthalaly|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/fr/2005/06/17/stories/2005061703310300.htm
|title=Parineeta: Sensuous and crisp}}</ref>

The issue of piracy cropped up when a news article published in ''[[The Indian Express]]'' exposed the dark side of the film market. Hardly into weeks of the film's release, [[CD]]'s were being sold at as low as Rs. 40.<ref name="expresscontro">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=135783
|title=National awards: Big B, Sarika win top honours}}</ref> Another blemish for the film was that Soumitra Dasgupta, a writer and close associate of Sarkar alleged that, the film's story had a striking resemblance to his parallel work on the novella.<ref name="timescontro">{{cite news|first=Bhaarati K.|last=Dubey|accessdate=2007-10-27|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1263298.cms
|title=Writer claims credit for Parineeta}}</ref>

=== Awards ===
Apart from winning the National Award for the Best First Film Director<ref name="ref39">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-12-07|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2263775.cms
|title=National awards: Big B, Sarika win top honours}}</ref>, ''Parineeta'' won five [[Filmfare Awards]]. [[Filmfare Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] to Keshto Mondal, Tanushree Sarkar and [[Pradeep Sarkar]], [[Filmfare Best Choreography Award|Best Choreography]] to Howard Rosemayer, [[Filmfare Best Debut Award|Best Debut]] to [[Vidya Balan]], [[Filmfare RD Burman Award for New Music Talent|RD Burman Award]] to Shantanu Moitra and [[Filmfare Best Sound|Best Sound Recording]] to Bishwadeep Chatterjee. It was also nominated for an additional nine awards which ranged from the categories for ''Best Film'', ''Best Director'', three for actors portraying Lolita, Shekhar and Girish to four nominations for the soundtrack. 

The film also won a prominent awards in the form of two [[Star Screen Awards]], three [[Zee Cine Awards]] among a notable awards. Apart from these, the film was nominated for an eclectic mix of awards.<ref name="indiafmawards">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-12-07|url=http://www.movietalkies.com/movies/movie-awards.asp?MovieId=17982
|title=Parineeta (2005): Awards & Nominations}}</ref>

== Screening at Film Festivals ==
In 2005, ''Parineeta'''s cast got a [[red carpet]] walk when it was the 'World Premiere Film' at the [[IIFA Awards|International Indian Film Awards]] (IIFA) weekend in Amsterdam.<ref name="IIFA1">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://www.hindu.com/mag/2005/06/26/stories/2005062600120200.htm|first=Susan|last=Muthalaly|title= Bollywood's mark on the tulip fields}}</ref> Owing to this European premiere, Sarkar said that the film had a great opening in the [[United States|American]] and [[England|English]] box-offices.<ref name="IIFA1">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://www.hindu.com/mag/2005/06/26/stories/2005062600120200.htm|first=Susan|last=Muthalaly|title= Bollywood's mark on the tulip fields}}</ref> True to his word, the movie was on the [[United Kingdom|UK]] Top Ten films for four consecutive weeks.<ref name="UKopening">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://chennaionline.com/film/Events/2006/06iifa.asp|first=R|last=Rangaraj|title=IIFA to showcase South films in Dubai}}</ref>

The film was chosen among 15 debut works for the 2006 [[Berlin Film Festival]].<ref name="sifyberlin">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://sify.com/movies/bollywood/fullstory.php?id=14122915||title=Parineeta chosen for Berlin Film Festival}}</ref><ref name="berlinale">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/2006/08_pressemitteilungen_2006/08_Pressemitteilungen_2006-Detail_2782.html||title=Press Release - Jan 20, 2006}}</ref> The film received enthusiastic reception from the audience as it ran to packed houses to the Chopra's surprise. Expecting an audience of about 100 Westerners, a critic visiting the festival was surprised to see the cinema hall full and people jostling for seats even on the steps.<ref name="dwelle">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://dwelle.de/southasia/1.171968.1.html|first=Preeti|last=John|title=Parineeta chosen for Berlin Film Festival}}</ref>

At the 24th Annual [[Minneapolis-St. Paul International Film Festival]] held in April 2006, ''Parineeta'' was the only [[India]]n mainstream cinema to feature among 135 films from 40 countries.<ref name="Stpaulfilmfest">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://www.mnfilmarts.org/m-spiff/2006/index2.html|title=24th Annual Minneapolis-St. Paul International Film Festival}}</ref>

In 2006, the film featured in the [[Palm Springs International Film Festival]]<ref name="palmsprings">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|url=http://128.97.165.17/showevent.asp?eventid=3995|first=Therese|last=Hayes|title=2006 Palm Springs International Film Festival}}</ref>, 24th [[San Francisco International Asian American Film Festival]]<ref name="sffilm">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|title=24th San Francisco International Asian American Film Festival|url=http://2006.asianamericanfilmfestival.org/downloads/press/2006_indian.pdf}}</ref>, [[Indian Film Festival of Los Angeles]]<ref name="lafilm">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|title=2006 Indian Film Festival of Los Angeles|url=http://www.indianfilmfestival.org/line_up_release.html}}</ref>, [[Helsinki Film Festival]]<ref name="helsinkifilm">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|title=2006 Helsinki Film Festival|url=http://2006.hiff.fi/elokuvat/elokuva.html?elokuva_id=162}}</ref> and the [[International Film Festival of Marrakech]].<ref name="marrakechfilm">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-26|title=6th International Film Festival of Marrakech|url=http://www.festivalmarrakech.info/Sunday-3-December-2006_a368.html}}</ref>

== DVD and Soundtrack ==
[[Image:Parineetadvd.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Parineeta DVD Cover]]
=== DVD ===
The first version of the DVD version of ''Parineeta'' was released by [[UTV Motion Pictures]] on [[October 30]], [[2006]]. It has subtitle options in English, Arabic, Spanish, German, Italian, Malay, and French. An additional disc includes interviews with the actors and a behind the scenes look at the making of the film. It is available in [[Aspect ratio (image)#16:9 standard|16:9]] [[Anamorphic widescreen]], [[Dolby Digital#Dolby Digital Surround EX|Dolby Digital 5.1 Surround]], [[Progressive scan|progressive]] 24 [[Frame rate|FPS]], [[widescreen]] and [[NTSC]] format.<ref name="ref6">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-20|url=http://store.nehaflix.com/pasdudvd.html|title=Parineeta DVD - Nehaflix.com}}</ref><ref name="ref8">{{cite news|accessdate=2007-10-20|url=http://www.amazon.co.uk/Parineeta-Sanjay-Dutt-Vidhya-Balan/dp/B000JLSR64/ref=pd_sbs_d_h__1/203-9883271-1404731|title=Parineeta DVD - Amazon.co.uk}}</ref>

=== Soundtrack ===
The soundtrack to ''Parineeta'' was released in April 2005 to positive reviews.<ref name="music">{{cite news|title=Music Review - Parineeta|accessdate=2007-10-20|url=http://www.planetbollywood.com/Music/Parineeta/}}</ref>

*'''[[Piyu Bole]]''' (4:21) sung by [[Sonu Nigam]] & [[Shreya Ghoshal]]. This song come when Shekhar asks Lolita to put some words in the tune he composed.
*'''[[Kasto Mazza]]''' (4:43) sung by [[Sonu Nigam]] & [[Shreya Ghoshal]]. Shekhar sings while traveling by train when he misses his beloved Lolita.
*'''[[Soona Man Ka Aangan]]''' (4:20) sung by [[Sonu Nigam]] & [[Shreya Ghoshal]]. A mellifluous and an emotional song sung by Shekhar, when he remembers his lifelong friendship with Lolita.
*'''[[Kaisi Paheli Zindgani]]''' (4:03) sung by [[Sunidhi Chauhan]]. A vibrant and pacy song which is about riddle of love which is complicated and painful and sometime happy.
*'''Raat Hamari Toh''' (5:19) sung by [[Chitra]] & [[Swanand]]. A soulful song sung by Lolita about her loneliness for a situation in the darkness of night.
*'''Dhinak Dhinak Dha''' (3:53) sung by [[Rita Ganguly]]. A song sung during Shekhar and Gayatri's wedding, shown once at the beginning and again when the film completes a full circle.
*'''[[Hui Main Parineeta]]''' (2:32) sung by [[Sonu Nigam]] & [[Shreya Ghoshal]]. Similar music to [[Piyu Bole]], but a slow and a smooth version picturized on Shekhar and Lolita's secret marriage and eventual lovemaking.

